name: Neuromuscular junction
question1: Describe the chain of events from AP to Excitation-Contraction coupling
contents:
• 1) Skeletal muscle Action Potential → (triggers)? Voltage gated Ca2+ channels
  • 2) Causes the FUSION of vesicles of ACh to the pre-synaptic Motor Neuron.
  • 3) EXOCYTOSIS → of ACh into the pre-synpatic cleft
  • 4) 2 ACh molecules bind to the post-synaptic ACh receptor (which is a NICOTINIC ACh receptor) - pentameric.
  • 5) If the END-PLATE-POTENTIAL is > 15mV then Na+ gated channels open (Na+ are in the t-tubules)
  • 6) Depolarisation of T-Tubules causes the release of Ca2+ from Sarcoplasmic reticulum
  • 7) Ca2+ induced Ca2+ release increases the amount of Ca2+ by +ve feedback. (via the Ryanodine receptor)
  • 8) Ca2+ then bids to the Tropomyosin head → causing a conformational change to expose the Actin binding site.


Excitation Myosin → Actin coupling

  • 1) Myosin binding site exposed - ActIn (thin) → Power-stroke
  • 2) ATP causes the release and re-setting of the head.
contents2:
Sarcomere is the basic unit of skeletal muscle cells

  • A typical resting sarcomere length is 2.2 μm
  • Sarcomere divided into:
  • I bands (isotropic) = ACTIN only
  • A bands (anisotropic) = MYOSIN with some ACTIN overlap
  • MYOSIN only
  • H zone (Heller = brighter) = myosin only
  • M line (Mittelscheibe) = central line of H zone
  • Z line (Zwischenscheibe) = anchor point of actin, dark band (junctin between neightbouring actin filaments, for forms the border between sacromeres)


From the Middle out :

M, H, A, I, Z.

isotropic: Properties of a material are identical in all directions. 

anisotropic: Properties of a material depend on the direction; for example, wood. In a piece of wood, you can see lines going in one direction; this direction is referred to as "with the grain".
